{"title_page": "FromSoftware", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = FromSoftware, Inc.\n| logo = Fromsoftware logo.svg\n| native_name = {{nowrap|\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30d5\u30ed\u30e0\u30fb\u30bd\u30d5\u30c8\u30a6\u30a7\u30a2}}\n| native_name_lang = ja\n| romanized_name = Kabushiki gaisha furomu sofutowea\n| type = {{ubl|[[Kabushiki gaisha]]|subsidiary}}\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1986|11|1}}\n| hq_location_city = Tokyo\n| hq_location_country = Japan\n| key_people = {{ubl|[[Hidetaka Miyazaki]]|{{small|([[President (corporate title)|President]])}}<ref name=\"company_info\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fromsoftware.jp/ww/company_about.html|title=Company|accessdate=May 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504121022/http://fromsoftware.jp/ww/company_about.html|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>|Masanori Takeuchi|{{small|(Senior Managing Director)}}<ref name=\"company_info\"/>}}\n| industry = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| products = {{ubl|''[[King's Field]]''|''[[Armored Core]]''|''[[Souls (series)|Souls]]''|''[[Bloodborne]]|''|''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]''}}\n| num_employees = 288\n| num_employees_year = 2019<ref name=\"company_info\"/>\n| parent = [[Kadokawa Corporation]]\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.fromsoftware.jp/ww/}}\n}}\n\n'''FromSoftware, Inc.''' is a Japanese [[video game development]] company founded in November 1986. The company is best known for the ''[[Armored Core]]'' and ''[[Souls (series)|Souls]]'' series, as well as ''[[Bloodborne]]'' and ''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]''.\n\n==History==\nFromSoftware was founded as a [[productivity software]] developer in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]], on November 1, 1986. Their first video game did not come until 1994, when they released ''[[King's Field (video game)|King's Field]]'' as a launch title for the [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/16/the-history-of-from-software|title=The History of From Software|first=Todd|last=Ciolek|date=March 16, 2015|website=ign.com|accessdate=April 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318103835/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/16/the-history-of-from-software|archive-date=March 18, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The game did not see a release in North America, although a 1995 sequel would later be released in North America bearing the same title, which was released as ''[[King's Field II]]'' in Japan. After releasing a third title in that series, FromSoftware moved on to release ''[[Echo Night]]'' as well as ''[[Shadow Tower]]'' in 1998. IGN would later note that the latter was \"effectively a ''King's Field'' follow-up\" as it shared many of the gameplay conventions with it. Also during this time FromSoftware would release ''[[Armored Core]]'', the first in a [[mech]] game series which would go on to spawn many sequels.<ref name=ignhistory>{{cite web|last1=Ciolek|first1=Todd|title=The History of From Software|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/16/the-history-of-from-software|website=IGN|accessdate=May 20, 2017|page=1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318103835/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/16/the-history-of-from-software|archive-date=March 18, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The making of ''Armored Core'' solidified the company's development skills, and in July, 1999, they released the multiplayer action game ''[[Frame Gride]]'' for the [[Sega]] [[Dreamcast]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fromsoftware.jp/ww/company_history.html|title=Historty {{!}} FromSoftware|website=www.fromsoftware.jp|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nWhen the [[PlayStation 2]] was launched in 2000, FromSoftware supported the system with two RPGs ''[[Eternal Ring]]'', which like the ''King's Field'' series is a first person RPG, and ''[[Evergrace]]'', a more conventional action RPG viewed from a third person perspective.<ref name=ignhistory/> In addition to these titles, FromSoftware published ''[[Tenchu: Wrath of Heaven]]'', a [[stealth game]] that combines action and adventure elements.<ref name=\":0\" /> The company also released a pair of sequels to their PlayStation 1 offerings with ''[[King's Field IV]]'' and ''[[Shadow Tower Abyss]]''.<ref name=ignhistory/> FromSoftware also released the ''Lost Kingdom'' titles for the [[Gamecube]], a competing sixth generation console.<ref name=ignhistory/> IGN would note however that during this generation FromSoftware's focus would shift from RPGs to mech games due in part to the success of the ''Armored Core'' series. In 2002, FromSoftware released the mech action game ''[[Murakumo: Renegade Mech Pursuit]]'' for the [[Xbox]] before entering the mobile game market, where they released another ''King's Field'' title.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2004, they released another Xbox title, ''[[Metal Wolf Chaos]].'' In 2005, FromSoftware would start to produce a series of licensed games based on the various [[anime]] properties under the banner ''Another Century's Episode''.<ref name=ignhistory/> In the same year, the company hosted the video game industry's first internship that let students experience game development through a game creation kit, ''Adventure Playe''r, for the [[PlayStation Portable]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2008, FromSoftware underwent a stock split before entering the [[Nintendo wii|Nintendo Wii]] market to release [[Tenchu: Shadow Assassins|''Tenchu: Shadow Assassins'']].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn April 2014, [[Kadokawa Corporation]] announced its intention to purchase the company from former shareholder Transcosmos. The deal was finalized on May 21, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/04/28/from-software-acquired-by-japanese-publisher-kadokawa-games/|title=From Software acquired by Japanese publisher Kadokawa Corporation|accessdate=April 28, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429181341/http://www.joystiq.com/2014/04/28/from-software-acquired-by-japanese-publisher-kadokawa-games/|archive-date=April 29, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In December 2015, FromSoftware was nominated for developer of the year at [[The Game Awards 2015]], but lost to [[CD Projekt Red]].<ref name=\"TGA: Nominees\">{{cite web|url=http://thegameawards.com/nominees/ |title=Nominees {{!}} The Game Awards 2015 |date=November 12, 2015 |website=[[The Game Awards]] |publisher=[[Ola Balola]] |accessdate=November 13, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151114024126/http://thegameawards.com/nominees/ |archivedate=November 14, 2015 }}</ref> In January 2016, FromSoftware added a new studio in [[Fukuoka]] that focuses on creating [[computer-generated imagery]] (CGI) assets for their games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2015/09/from-software-open-new-studio-fukuoka|title=From Software to open new studio in Fukuoka|date=September 12, 2015|website=Gematsu|access-date=September 15, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916034650/http://gematsu.com/2015/09/from-software-open-new-studio-fukuoka|archive-date=September 16, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=FromSoftware to Establish New Studio in Fukuoka in October 2015|url=http://fromsoftware.jp/pc_en/news/pressrelease/20150912_fukuokastudio_pressrelease.html|publisher=FromSoftware|accessdate=June 25, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601104053/http://www.fromsoftware.jp/pc_en/news/pressrelease/20150912_fukuokastudio_pressrelease.html|archive-date=June 1, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Games==\nFromSoftware have developed for a wide range of platforms, including the [[Dreamcast]], [[Nintendo DS]], [[GameCube]], [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]], [[PlayStation 2]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], [[Xbox 360]], [[Xbox One]], [[PlayStation Portable]], [[Wii]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Nintendo Switch]], and various mobile devices.\n\nWith fifteen titles developed, the ''[[Armored Core (series)|Armored Core]]'' series is the studio's longest running franchise. The most recent title, ''[[Armored Core: Verdict Day]]'', was released worldwide in September 2013 for the PlayStation 3 and Xbox 360. Earlier, less notable outside Japan, titles include the ''[[Enchanted Arms]]'', ''[[King's Field (series)|King's Field]]'', ''[[Chromehounds]]'', ''[[Otogi]]'', and ''[[Tenchu]]'' series, all of which have been met with mostly favorable reviews.\n\nIn 2009, they released ''[[Demon's Souls]]'' for the [[PlayStation 3]], which brought them international exposure. Its [[spiritual successor]], ''[[Dark Souls]]'', was released in 2011. In March 2014, ''[[Dark Souls II]]'', was released, while ''[[Dark Souls III]]'' was released in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dark Souls 3 confirmed, coming early 2016|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/6/15/8782845/dark-souls-3-announced-e3-2015-from-software|website=Polygon|accessdate=October 2, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924182414/http://www.polygon.com/2015/6/15/8782845/dark-souls-3-announced-e3-2015-from-software|archive-date=September 24, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|date=June 15, 2015}}</ref> A title inspired by the ''Souls'' series, ''[[Bloodborne]]'', was released in March 2015. The ''[[Souls (series)|Souls series]]'', along with ''Bloodborne'', received widespread critical acclaim, as well as strong sales domestically and internationally.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.psxextreme.com/ps3-news/4604.html |author=Ben Dutka |title=Demon's Souls Caps Impressive First Week of Sales in Japan |publisher=PSX Extreme |date=February 12, 2009 |accessdate=March 17, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320070828/http://www.psxextreme.com/ps3-news/4604.html |archive-date=March 20, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>May 8, 2014, [http://www.bandainamco.co.jp/files/E8A39CE8B6B3E8B387E69699EFBC88E88BB1EFBC89.pdf Financial Highlights for the Fiscal Year Ended March 2014] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508123624/http://www.bandainamco.co.jp/files/E8A39CE8B6B3E8B387E69699EFBC88E88BB1EFBC89.pdf |date=May 8, 2014 }}, NAMCO BANDAI Holdings Inc.</ref><ref>May 7, 2014, [http://www.siliconera.com/2014/05/07/dark-souls-ii-ships-1-2-million-u-s-europe/ Dark Souls II Ships 1.2 Million In U.S. And Europe] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402112324/http://www.siliconera.com/2014/05/07/dark-souls-ii-ships-1-2-million-u-s-europe/ |date=April 2, 2015 }}, Siliconera</ref> They have also received a number of awards, primarily those for the [[role-playing video game|role-playing]] genre, including multiple \"RPG of the Year\" and [[Game of the Year]] awards.<ref>{{cite web |first=Adriaan |last=den Ouden |title=RPG of the Year |url=http://www.rpgamer.com/awards/2009/results/rpg_oty.html |publisher=RPGamer |accessdate=March 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100401203901/http://www.rpgamer.com/awards/2009/results/rpg_oty.html |archive-date=April 1, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Marchello |title=Best Graphics |url=http://www.rpgamer.com/awards/2009/results/graphics.html |publisher=RPGamer |accessdate=March 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100410020905/http://www.rpgamer.com/awards/2009/results/graphics.html |archive-date=April 10, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Ken |last=Staples |title=Best PS3 |url=http://www.rpgamer.com/awards/2009/results/ps3.html |publisher=RPGamer |accessdate=March 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100406011933/http://www.rpgamer.com/awards/2009/results/ps3.html |archive-date=April 6, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Community Choice Game of the Year|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/news/community-choice-game-of-the-year-10205|work=[[Game Revolution]]|accessdate=December 31, 2011|date=December 23, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130402080913/http://www.gamerevolution.com/news/community-choice-game-of-the-year-10205|archive-date=April 2, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Since release, ''Dark Souls'' and ''Bloodborne'' have been cited by many publications to be among the [[greatest games of all time]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Polygon Staff|title=The 500 Best Video Games of All Time|url=https://www.polygon.com/features/2017/11/27/16158276/polygon-500-best-games-of-all-time-500-401|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon.com]]|accessdate=December 1, 2017|date=November 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303210843/https://www.polygon.com/features/2017/11/27/16158276/polygon-500-best-games-of-all-time-500-401|archive-date=March 3, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Game Informer]]|title=The Top 300 Games of All Time|date=April 2018|issue=300}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Edge Presents: The 100 Greatest Video Games of All Time|magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]|date=August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, FromSoftware revealed that they were working on a new intellectual property, as well as stating their intent to return to the ''Armored Core'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/04/27/dark-souls-3-director-already-working-on-a-new-ip/|title=Dark Souls 3 director already working on a new IP|first=Brenna|last=Hillier|work=[[VG247]]|date=April 27, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160428104541/http://www.vg247.com/2016/04/27/dark-souls-3-director-already-working-on-a-new-ip/|archive-date=April 28, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Two games, the [[PlayStation VR]] exclusive ''[[D\u00e9racin\u00e9]]'' and the multiplatform ''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]'', were announced at [[E3 2018]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=McWhertor |first1=Michael |title=FromSoftware's Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice coming from Activision |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/10/17446826/shadows-die-twice-from-software-activision-announcement |website=Polygon |accessdate=11 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141020/https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/10/17446826/shadows-die-twice-from-software-activision-announcement |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all |date=June 10, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Statt |first1=Nick |title=Dark Souls creator From Software is making a VR game called D\u00e9racin\u00e9 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/6/11/17452096/from-software-deracine-announced-virtual-reality-sony-ps-vr-e3-2018 |website=The Verge |accessdate=12 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140127/https://www.theverge.com/2018/6/11/17452096/from-software-deracine-announced-virtual-reality-sony-ps-vr-e3-2018 |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all |date=June 12, 2018 }}</ref> At [[E3 2019]], an action role-playing game featuring the collaboration of Miyazaki and ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire]]'' series author [[George R. R. Martin]] was announced, titled ''[[Elden Ring]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McWhertor |first1=Michael |title=Elden Ring, a game from George R.R. Martin and FromSoftware, has been revealed |website=Polygon |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2019/6/9/18658005/elden-ring-from-software-e3-2019-trailer-release-date-george-rr-martin |accessdate=9 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610143838/https://www.polygon.com/e3/2019/6/9/18658005/elden-ring-from-software-e3-2019-trailer-release-date-george-rr-martin |archive-date=June 10, 2019 |url-status=live |date=June 9, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" width=\"auto\"\n|+List of games developed by FromSoftware<ref>{{cite web|title=Products|url=http://www.fromsoftware.jp/ww/products.html|website=fromsoftware.jp|accessdate=8 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509080334/http://www.fromsoftware.jp/ww/products.html|archive-date=May 9, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n! Title\n! System\n! Initial release\n|-\n| ''[[King's Field (video game)|King's Field]]''\n| rowspan=\"9\" | [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]]\n| {{dts|December 16, 1994}}\n|-\n| ''[[King's Field II]]''\n| {{dts|July 21, 1995}}\n|-\n| ''[[King's Field III]]''\n| {{dts|June 21, 1996}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core (video game)|Armored Core]]''\n| {{dts|July 10, 1997}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core: Project Phantasma]]''\n| {{dts|December 4, 1997}}\n|-\n| ''[[Shadow Tower]]''\n| {{dts|June 25, 1998}}\n|-\n| ''[[Echo Night]]''\n| {{dts|August 13, 1998}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core: Master of Arena]]''\n| {{dts|February 4, 1999}}\n|-\n| ''[[Spriggan (manga)#Video game|Spriggan: Lunar Verse]]''\n| {{dts|June 16, 1999}}\n|-\n| ''[[Frame Gride]]''\n| [[Dreamcast]]\n| {{dts|July 15, 1999}}\n|-\n| ''[[Echo Night 2: The Lord of Nightmares]]''\n| PlayStation\n| {{dts|August 5, 1999}}\n|-\n| ''[[Eternal Ring]]''\n| rowspan=\"8\" | [[PlayStation 2]]\n| {{dts|March 4, 2000}}\n|-\n| ''[[Evergrace]]''\n| {{dts|April 27, 2000}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core 2]]''\n| {{dts|August 3, 2000}}\n|-\n| ''[[The Adventures of Cookie & Cream]]''\n| {{dts|December 7, 2000}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core 2: Another Age]]''\n| {{dts|April 12, 2001}}\n|-\n| ''[[Forever Kingdom]]''\n| {{dts|June 21, 2001}}\n|-\n| ''[[King's Field IV]]''\n| {{dts|October 4, 2001}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core 3]]''\n| {{dts|April 1, 2002}}\n|-\n| ''[[Lost Kingdoms]]''\n| [[GameCube]]\n| {{dts|April 25, 2002}}\n|-\n| ''[[Otogi: Myth of Demons]]''\n| [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]]\n| {{dts|December 12, 2002}}\n|-\n| ''[[Silent Line: Armored Core|Armored Core: Silent Line]]''\n| PlayStation 2\n| {{dts|January 23, 2003}}\n|-\n| ''[[Murakumo: Renegade Mech Pursuit]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Xbox\n| {{dts|July 25, 2002}}\n|-\n| ''Thousand Land''\n| {{dts|March 20, 2003}}\n|-\n| ''[[Lost Kingdoms II]]''\n| GameCube\n| {{dts|May 23, 2003}}\n|-\n| ''[[Shadow Tower Abyss]]''\n| PlayStation 2\n| {{dts|October 23, 2003}}\n|-\n| ''[[Otogi 2: Immortal Warriors]]''\n| Xbox\n| {{dts|December 25, 2003}}\n|-\n| ''[[Echo Night: Beyond|Nebula: Echo Night]]''\n| rowspan=\"4\" | PlayStation 2\n| {{dts|January 22, 2004}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core: Nexus]]''\n| {{dts|March 18, 2004}}\n|-\n| ''[[Kuon]]''\n| {{dts|April 1, 2004}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core: Nine Breaker]]''\n| {{dts|October 28, 2004}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core: Formula Front]]''\n| [[PlayStation Portable]]\n| {{dts|December 12, 2004}}\n|-\n| ''[[Metal Wolf Chaos]]''\n| Xbox\n| {{dts|December 22, 2004}}\n|-\n| ''[[Yoshitsune Eiy\u016bden: The Story of Hero Yoshitsune]]''\n| rowspan=\"4\" | PlayStation 2\n| {{dts|January 13, 2005}}\n|-\n| ''[[Another Century's Episode]]''\n| {{dts|January 27, 2005}}\n|-\n| ''Yoshitsune Eiyuuden Shura: The Story of Hero Yoshitsune Shura''\n| {{dts|May 27, 2005}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core: Last Raven]]''\n| {{dts|August 4, 2005}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | ''[[Enchanted Arms]]''\n| [[PlayStation 3]]\n| rowspan=2 | {{dts|January 12, 2006}}\n|-\n| [[Xbox 360]]\n|-\n| ''[[Another Century's Episode 2]]''\n| PlayStation 2\n| {{dts|March 30, 2006}}\n|-\n| ''[[Chromehounds]]''\n| Xbox 360\n| {{dts|June 29, 2006}}\n|-\n| ''King's Field: Additional I''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | PlayStation Portable\n| {{dts|July 20, 2006}}\n|-\n| ''King's Field: Additional II''\n| {{dts|August 24, 2006}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | ''[[Armored Core 4]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| rowspan=2 | {{dts|December 21, 2006}}\n|-\n| Xbox 360\n|-\n| ''Nanpure VOW''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Nintendo DS]]\n| {{dts|April 26, 2007}}\n|-\n| ''Iraroji VOW''\n| {{dts|May 24, 2007}}\n|-\n| ''[[Another Century's Episode 3: The Final]]''\n| PlayStation 2\n| {{dts|September 6, 2007}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | ''[[Armored Core: For Answer]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| rowspan=2 | {{dts|March 19, 2008}}\n|-\n| Xbox 360\n|-\n| ''[[Shadow Assault: Tenchu]]''\n| Xbox 360\n| {{dts|October 8, 2008}}\n|-\n| ''Inugamike no Ichizoku''\n| Nintendo DS\n| {{dts|January 22, 2009}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | ''[[Ninja Blade]]''\n| Xbox 360\n| rowspan=2 | {{dts|January 29, 2009}}\n|-\n| [[Microsoft Windows]]\n|-\n| ''[[Demon's Souls]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| {{dts|February 5, 2009}}\n|-\n| ''Yatsu Hakamura''\n| Nintendo DS\n| {{dts|April 23, 2009}}\n|-\n| ''[[Another Century's Episode: R]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| {{dts|August 19, 2010}}\n|-\n| ''[[Monster Hunter Diary: Poka Poka Airou Village]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | PlayStation Portable\n| {{dts|August 26, 2010}}\n|-\n| ''[[Another Century's Episode Portable]]''\n| {{dts|January 13, 2011}}\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | ''[[Dark Souls]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{dts|September 22, 2011}}\n|-\n| Xbox 360\n|-\n| Microsoft Windows\n| {{dts|August 23, 2012}}\n|-\n| Nintendo Switch\n| {{dts|October 19, 2018}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[Armored Core V]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{dts|January 26, 2012}}\n|-\n| Xbox 360\n|-\n| ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam Unicorn (video game)|Mobile Suit Gundam Unicorn]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| {{dts|March 8, 2012}}\n|-\n| ''[[Steel Battalion: Heavy Armor]]''\n| Xbox 360\n| {{dts|June 21, 2012}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | ''[[Armored Core: Verdict Day]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| rowspan=2 | {{dts|September 26, 2013}}\n|-\n|Xbox 360\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | ''[[Dark Souls II]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| rowspan=3 | {{dts|March 13, 2014}}\n|-\n| Xbox 360\n|-\n| Microsoft Windows\n|-\n| rowspan=5 | ''[[Dark Souls II: Scholar of the First Sin]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| rowspan=5 | {{dts|February 5, 2015}}\n|-\n| Xbox 360\n|-\n| [[PlayStation 4]]\n|-\n| [[Xbox One]]\n|-\n| Microsoft Windows\n|-\n| ''[[Bloodborne]]''\n| PlayStation 4\n| {{dts|March 24, 2015}}\n|-\n| ''[[Monster Hunter Diary: Poka Poka Airou Village DX]]''\n| [[Nintendo 3DS]]\n| {{dts|September 10, 2015}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | ''[[Dark Souls III]]''\n| PlayStation 4\n| rowspan=2 | {{dts|March 24, 2016}}\n|-\n| Xbox One\n|-\n| Microsoft Windows\n| {{dts|April 12, 2016}}\n|-\n| ''[[D\u00e9racin\u00e9]]''\n| PlayStation 4 ([[PlayStation VR]])\n| {{dts|November 6, 2018}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | ''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]''\n| Microsoft Windows\n| rowspan=3 | {{dts|March 22, 2019}}\n|-\n| PlayStation 4\n|-\n| Xbox One\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | ''[[Elden Ring]]''\n| Microsoft Windows\n| rowspan=3 | TBA\n|-\n| PlayStation 4\n|-\n| Xbox One\n|}\n\n== Game Philosophy ==\nFromSoftware is known for releasing highly difficult titles, notably the ''Souls series'', ''Bloodborne'', and ''Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice'', that lack difficulty settings.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vgr.com/fromsoftware-explains-why-its-games-dont-have-difficulty-levels/|title=FromSoftware Explains Why Its Games Don\u2019t Have Difficulty Levels|last=VGR|date=2018-06-19|website=VGR|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> [[Hidetaka Miyazaki]], the President of FromSoftware, justified the lack of difficulty settings, stating, \"We don't want to include a difficulty selection because we want to bring everyone to the same level of discussion and the same level of enjoyment. So we want everyone...to first face that challenge and to overcome it in some way that suits them as a player. We want everyone to feel that sense of accomplishment. We want everyone to feel elated and to join that discussion on the same level. We feel if there's different difficulties, that's going to segment and fragment the user base. People will have different experiences based on that [differing difficulty level]. This is something we take to heart when we design games. It's been the same way for previous titles and it's very much the same with ''Sekiro''.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.fromsoftware.jp/ww/}}\n\n{{FromSoftware games}}\n{{Kadokawa Dwango}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1986 establishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Software companies based in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Kadokawa Corporation subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:Japanese brands]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of Japan]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:Video game publishers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = FromSoftware, Inc.\n| logo = Fromsoftware logo.svg\n| native_name = {{nowrap|\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30d5\u30ed\u30e0\u30fb\u30bd\u30d5\u30c8\u30a6\u30a7\u30a2}}\n| native_name_lang = ja\n| romanized_name = Kabushiki gaisha furomu sofutowea\n| type = {{ubl|[[Kabushiki gaisha]]|subsidiary}}\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1986|11|1}}\n| hq_location_city = Tokyo\n| hq_location_country = Japan\n| key_people = {{ubl|[[Hidetaka Miyazaki]]|{{small|([[President (corporate title)|President]])}}<ref name=\"company_info\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fromsoftware.jp/ww/company_about.html|title=Company|accessdate=May 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504121022/http://fromsoftware.jp/ww/company_about.html|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>|Masanori Takeuchi|{{small|(Senior Managing Director)}}<ref name=\"company_info\"/>}}\n| industry = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| products = {{ubl|''[[King's Field]]''|''[[Armored Core]]''|''[[Souls (series)|Souls]]''|''[[Bloodborne]]|''|''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]''}}\n| num_employees = 288\n| num_employees_year = 2019<ref name=\"company_info\"/>\n| parent = [[Kadokawa Corporation]]\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.fromsoftware.jp/ww/}}\n}}\n\n'''FromSoftware, Inc.''' is a Japanese [[video game development]] company founded in November 1986. The company is best known for the ''[[Armored Core]]'' and ''[[Souls (series)|Souls]]'' series, as well as ''[[Bloodborne]]'' and ''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]''.\n\n==History==\nFromSoftware was founded as a [[productivity software]] developer in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]], on November 1, 1986. Their first video game did not come until 1994, when they released ''[[King's Field (video game)|King's Field]]'' as a launch title for the [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/16/the-history-of-from-software|title=The History of From Software|first=Todd|last=Ciolek|date=March 16, 2015|website=ign.com|accessdate=April 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318103835/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/16/the-history-of-from-software|archive-date=March 18, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The game did not see a release in North America, although a 1995 sequel would later be released in North America bearing the same title, which was released as ''[[King's Field II]]'' in Japan. After releasing a third title in that series, FromSoftware moved on to release ''[[Echo Night]]'' as well as ''[[Shadow Tower]]'' in 1998. IGN would later note that the latter was \"effectively a ''King's Field'' follow-up\" as it shared many of the gameplay conventions with it. Also during this time FromSoftware would release ''[[Armored Core]]'', the first in a [[mech]] game series which would go on to spawn many sequels.<ref name=ignhistory>{{cite web|last1=Ciolek|first1=Todd|title=The History of From Software|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/16/the-history-of-from-software|website=IGN|accessdate=May 20, 2017|page=1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318103835/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/16/the-history-of-from-software|archive-date=March 18, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The making of ''Armored Core'' solidified the company's development skills, and in July, 1999, they released the multiplayer action game ''[[Frame Gride]]'' for the [[Sega]] [[Dreamcast]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fromsoftware.jp/ww/company_history.html|title=Historty {{!}} FromSoftware|website=www.fromsoftware.jp|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nWhen the [[PlayStation 2]] was launched in 2000, FromSoftware supported the system with two RPGs ''[[Eternal Ring]]'', which like the ''King's Field'' series is a first person RPG, and ''[[Evergrace]]'', a more conventional action RPG viewed from a third person perspective.<ref name=ignhistory/> In addition to these titles, FromSoftware published ''[[Tenchu: Wrath of Heaven]]'', a [[stealth game]] that combines action and adventure elements.<ref name=\":0\" /> The company also released a pair of sequels to their PlayStation 1 offerings with ''[[King's Field IV]]'' and ''[[Shadow Tower Abyss]]''.<ref name=ignhistory/> FromSoftware also released the ''Lost Kingdom'' titles for the [[Gamecube]], a competing sixth generation console.<ref name=ignhistory/> IGN would note however that during this generation FromSoftware's focus would shift from RPGs to mech games due in part to the success of the ''Armored Core'' series. In 2002, FromSoftware released the mech action game ''[[Murakumo: Renegade Mech Pursuit]]'' for the [[Xbox]] before entering the mobile game market, where they released another ''King's Field'' title.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2004, they released another Xbox title, ''[[Metal Wolf Chaos]].'' In 2005, FromSoftware would start to produce a series of licensed games based on the various [[anime]] properties under the banner ''Another Century's Episode''.<ref name=ignhistory/> In the same year, the company hosted the video game industry's first internship that let students experience game development through a game creation kit, ''Adventure Playe''r, for the [[PlayStation Portable]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2008, FromSoftware underwent a stock split before entering the [[Nintendo wii|Nintendo Wii]] market to release [[Tenchu: Shadow Assassins]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn April 2014, [[Kadokawa Corporation]] announced its intention to purchase the company from former shareholder Transcosmos. The deal was finalized on May 21, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/04/28/from-software-acquired-by-japanese-publisher-kadokawa-games/|title=From Software acquired by Japanese publisher Kadokawa Corporation|accessdate=April 28, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429181341/http://www.joystiq.com/2014/04/28/from-software-acquired-by-japanese-publisher-kadokawa-games/|archive-date=April 29, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In December 2015, FromSoftware was nominated for developer of the year at [[The Game Awards 2015]], but lost to [[CD Projekt Red]].<ref name=\"TGA: Nominees\">{{cite web|url=http://thegameawards.com/nominees/ |title=Nominees {{!}} The Game Awards 2015 |date=November 12, 2015 |website=[[The Game Awards]] |publisher=[[Ola Balola]] |accessdate=November 13, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151114024126/http://thegameawards.com/nominees/ |archivedate=November 14, 2015 }}</ref> In January 2016, FromSoftware added a new studio in [[Fukuoka]] that focuses on creating [[computer-generated imagery]] (CGI) assets for their games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2015/09/from-software-open-new-studio-fukuoka|title=From Software to open new studio in Fukuoka|date=September 12, 2015|website=Gematsu|access-date=September 15, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916034650/http://gematsu.com/2015/09/from-software-open-new-studio-fukuoka|archive-date=September 16, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=FromSoftware to Establish New Studio in Fukuoka in October 2015|url=http://fromsoftware.jp/pc_en/news/pressrelease/20150912_fukuokastudio_pressrelease.html|publisher=FromSoftware|accessdate=June 25, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601104053/http://www.fromsoftware.jp/pc_en/news/pressrelease/20150912_fukuokastudio_pressrelease.html|archive-date=June 1, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Games==\nFromSoftware have developed for a wide range of platforms, including the [[Dreamcast]], [[Nintendo DS]], [[GameCube]], [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]], [[PlayStation 2]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], [[Xbox 360]], [[Xbox One]], [[PlayStation Portable]], [[Wii]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Nintendo Switch]], and various mobile devices.\n\nWith fifteen titles developed, the ''[[Armored Core (series)|Armored Core]]'' series is the studio's longest running franchise. The most recent title, ''[[Armored Core: Verdict Day]]'', was released worldwide in September 2013 for the PlayStation 3 and Xbox 360. Earlier, less notable outside Japan, titles include the ''[[Enchanted Arms]]'', ''[[King's Field (series)|King's Field]]'', ''[[Chromehounds]]'', ''[[Otogi]]'', and ''[[Tenchu]]'' series, all of which have been met with mostly favorable reviews.\n\nIn 2009, they released ''[[Demon's Souls]]'' for the [[PlayStation 3]], which brought them international exposure. Its [[spiritual successor]], ''[[Dark Souls]]'', was released in 2011. In March 2014, ''[[Dark Souls II]]'', was released, while ''[[Dark Souls III]]'' was released in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dark Souls 3 confirmed, coming early 2016|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/6/15/8782845/dark-souls-3-announced-e3-2015-from-software|website=Polygon|accessdate=October 2, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924182414/http://www.polygon.com/2015/6/15/8782845/dark-souls-3-announced-e3-2015-from-software|archive-date=September 24, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all|date=June 15, 2015}}</ref> A title inspired by the ''Souls'' series, ''[[Bloodborne]]'', was released in March 2015. The ''[[Souls (series)|Souls series]]'', along with ''Bloodborne'', received widespread critical acclaim, as well as strong sales domestically and internationally.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.psxextreme.com/ps3-news/4604.html |author=Ben Dutka |title=Demon's Souls Caps Impressive First Week of Sales in Japan |publisher=PSX Extreme |date=February 12, 2009 |accessdate=March 17, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320070828/http://www.psxextreme.com/ps3-news/4604.html |archive-date=March 20, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>May 8, 2014, [http://www.bandainamco.co.jp/files/E8A39CE8B6B3E8B387E69699EFBC88E88BB1EFBC89.pdf Financial Highlights for the Fiscal Year Ended March 2014] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508123624/http://www.bandainamco.co.jp/files/E8A39CE8B6B3E8B387E69699EFBC88E88BB1EFBC89.pdf |date=May 8, 2014 }}, NAMCO BANDAI Holdings Inc.</ref><ref>May 7, 2014, [http://www.siliconera.com/2014/05/07/dark-souls-ii-ships-1-2-million-u-s-europe/ Dark Souls II Ships 1.2 Million In U.S. And Europe] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402112324/http://www.siliconera.com/2014/05/07/dark-souls-ii-ships-1-2-million-u-s-europe/ |date=April 2, 2015 }}, Siliconera</ref> They have also received a number of awards, primarily those for the [[role-playing video game|role-playing]] genre, including multiple \"RPG of the Year\" and [[Game of the Year]] awards.<ref>{{cite web |first=Adriaan |last=den Ouden |title=RPG of the Year |url=http://www.rpgamer.com/awards/2009/results/rpg_oty.html |publisher=RPGamer |accessdate=March 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100401203901/http://www.rpgamer.com/awards/2009/results/rpg_oty.html |archive-date=April 1, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Marchello |title=Best Graphics |url=http://www.rpgamer.com/awards/2009/results/graphics.html |publisher=RPGamer |accessdate=March 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100410020905/http://www.rpgamer.com/awards/2009/results/graphics.html |archive-date=April 10, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Ken |last=Staples |title=Best PS3 |url=http://www.rpgamer.com/awards/2009/results/ps3.html |publisher=RPGamer |accessdate=March 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100406011933/http://www.rpgamer.com/awards/2009/results/ps3.html |archive-date=April 6, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Community Choice Game of the Year|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/news/community-choice-game-of-the-year-10205|work=[[Game Revolution]]|accessdate=December 31, 2011|date=December 23, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130402080913/http://www.gamerevolution.com/news/community-choice-game-of-the-year-10205|archive-date=April 2, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Since release, ''Dark Souls'' and ''Bloodborne'' have been cited by many publications to be among the [[greatest games of all time]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Polygon Staff|title=The 500 Best Video Games of All Time|url=https://www.polygon.com/features/2017/11/27/16158276/polygon-500-best-games-of-all-time-500-401|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon.com]]|accessdate=December 1, 2017|date=November 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303210843/https://www.polygon.com/features/2017/11/27/16158276/polygon-500-best-games-of-all-time-500-401|archive-date=March 3, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Game Informer]]|title=The Top 300 Games of All Time|date=April 2018|issue=300}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Edge Presents: The 100 Greatest Video Games of All Time|magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]|date=August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, FromSoftware revealed that they were working on a new intellectual property, as well as stating their intent to return to the ''Armored Core'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2016/04/27/dark-souls-3-director-already-working-on-a-new-ip/|title=Dark Souls 3 director already working on a new IP|first=Brenna|last=Hillier|work=[[VG247]]|date=April 27, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160428104541/http://www.vg247.com/2016/04/27/dark-souls-3-director-already-working-on-a-new-ip/|archive-date=April 28, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Two games, the [[PlayStation VR]] exclusive ''[[D\u00e9racin\u00e9]]'' and the multiplatform ''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]'', were announced at [[E3 2018]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=McWhertor |first1=Michael |title=FromSoftware's Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice coming from Activision |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/10/17446826/shadows-die-twice-from-software-activision-announcement |website=Polygon |accessdate=11 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141020/https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/10/17446826/shadows-die-twice-from-software-activision-announcement |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all |date=June 10, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Statt |first1=Nick |title=Dark Souls creator From Software is making a VR game called D\u00e9racin\u00e9 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/6/11/17452096/from-software-deracine-announced-virtual-reality-sony-ps-vr-e3-2018 |website=The Verge |accessdate=12 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140127/https://www.theverge.com/2018/6/11/17452096/from-software-deracine-announced-virtual-reality-sony-ps-vr-e3-2018 |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all |date=June 12, 2018 }}</ref> At [[E3 2019]], an action role-playing game featuring the collaboration of Miyazaki and ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire]]'' series author [[George R. R. Martin]] was announced, titled ''[[Elden Ring]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McWhertor |first1=Michael |title=Elden Ring, a game from George R.R. Martin and FromSoftware, has been revealed |website=Polygon |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2019/6/9/18658005/elden-ring-from-software-e3-2019-trailer-release-date-george-rr-martin |accessdate=9 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610143838/https://www.polygon.com/e3/2019/6/9/18658005/elden-ring-from-software-e3-2019-trailer-release-date-george-rr-martin |archive-date=June 10, 2019 |url-status=live |date=June 9, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" width=\"auto\"\n|+List of games developed by FromSoftware<ref>{{cite web|title=Products|url=http://www.fromsoftware.jp/ww/products.html|website=fromsoftware.jp|accessdate=8 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509080334/http://www.fromsoftware.jp/ww/products.html|archive-date=May 9, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n! Title\n! System\n! Initial release\n|-\n| ''[[King's Field (video game)|King's Field]]''\n| rowspan=\"9\" | [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]]\n| {{dts|December 16, 1994}}\n|-\n| ''[[King's Field II]]''\n| {{dts|July 21, 1995}}\n|-\n| ''[[King's Field III]]''\n| {{dts|June 21, 1996}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core (video game)|Armored Core]]''\n| {{dts|July 10, 1997}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core: Project Phantasma]]''\n| {{dts|December 4, 1997}}\n|-\n| ''[[Shadow Tower]]''\n| {{dts|June 25, 1998}}\n|-\n| ''[[Echo Night]]''\n| {{dts|August 13, 1998}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core: Master of Arena]]''\n| {{dts|February 4, 1999}}\n|-\n| ''[[Spriggan (manga)#Video game|Spriggan: Lunar Verse]]''\n| {{dts|June 16, 1999}}\n|-\n| ''[[Frame Gride]]''\n| [[Dreamcast]]\n| {{dts|July 15, 1999}}\n|-\n| ''[[Echo Night 2: The Lord of Nightmares]]''\n| PlayStation\n| {{dts|August 5, 1999}}\n|-\n| ''[[Eternal Ring]]''\n| rowspan=\"8\" | [[PlayStation 2]]\n| {{dts|March 4, 2000}}\n|-\n| ''[[Evergrace]]''\n| {{dts|April 27, 2000}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core 2]]''\n| {{dts|August 3, 2000}}\n|-\n| ''[[The Adventures of Cookie & Cream]]''\n| {{dts|December 7, 2000}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core 2: Another Age]]''\n| {{dts|April 12, 2001}}\n|-\n| ''[[Forever Kingdom]]''\n| {{dts|June 21, 2001}}\n|-\n| ''[[King's Field IV]]''\n| {{dts|October 4, 2001}}\n|-\n| ''[[Armored Core 3]]''\n| {{dts|April 1, 2002}}\n|-\n| ''[[Lost Kingdoms]]''\n| [[GameCube]]\n| {{dts|April 25, 2002}}\n|-\n| ''[[Otogi: Myth of Demons]]''\n| [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]]\n| {{dts|December 12, 2002}}\n|-\n| ''[[Silent Line: Armored Core|Armored Core: Silent Line]]''\n| PlayStation 2\n| {{dts|January 23, 2003}}\n|-\n| ''[[Murakumo: Renegade Mech Pursuit]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Xbox\n| {{dts|July 25, 2002}}\n|-\n| ''Thousand Land''\n| {{dts|March 20, 2003}}\n|-\n| ''[[Lost Kingdoms II]]''\n| GameCube\n| {{dts|May 23, 2003}}\n|-\n| ''[[Shadow Tower Abyss]]''\n| PlayStation 2\n| {{dts|October 