Ninja Blade]]''\n| Xbox 360\n| rowspan=2 | {{dts|January 29, 2009}}\n|-\n| [[Microsoft Windows]]\n|-\n| ''[[Demon's Souls]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| {{dts|February 5, 2009}}\n|-\n| ''Yatsu Hakamura''\n| Nintendo DS\n| {{dts|April 23, 2009}}\n|-\n| ''[[Another Century's Episode: R]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| {{dts|August 19, 2010}}\n|-\n| ''[[Monster Hunter Diary: Poka Poka Airou Village]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | PlayStation Portable\n| {{dts|August 26, 2010}}\n|-\n| ''[[Another Century's Episode Portable]]''\n| {{dts|January 13, 2011}}\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | ''[[Dark Souls]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{dts|September 22, 2011}}\n|-\n| Xbox 360\n|-\n| Microsoft Windows\n| {{dts|August 23, 2012}}\n|-\n| Nintendo Switch\n| {{dts|October 19, 2018}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[Armored Core V]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{dts|January 26, 2012}}\n|-\n| Xbox 360\n|-\n| ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam Unicorn (video game)|Mobile Suit Gundam Unicorn]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| {{dts|March 8, 2012}}\n|-\n| ''[[Steel Battalion: Heavy Armor]]''\n| Xbox 360\n| {{dts|June 21, 2012}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | ''[[Armored Core: Verdict Day]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| rowspan=2 | {{dts|September 26, 2013}}\n|-\n|Xbox 360\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | ''[[Dark Souls II]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| rowspan=3 | {{dts|March 13, 2014}}\n|-\n| Xbox 360\n|-\n| Microsoft Windows\n|-\n| rowspan=5 | ''[[Dark Souls II: Scholar of the First Sin]]''\n| PlayStation 3\n| rowspan=5 | {{dts|February 5, 2015}}\n|-\n| Xbox 360\n|-\n| [[PlayStation 4]]\n|-\n| [[Xbox One]]\n|-\n| Microsoft Windows\n|-\n| ''[[Bloodborne]]''\n| PlayStation 4\n| {{dts|March 24, 2015}}\n|-\n| ''[[Monster Hunter Diary: Poka Poka Airou Village DX]]''\n| [[Nintendo 3DS]]\n| {{dts|September 10, 2015}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | ''[[Dark Souls III]]''\n| PlayStation 4\n| rowspan=2 | {{dts|March 24, 2016}}\n|-\n| Xbox One\n|-\n| Microsoft Windows\n| {{dts|April 12, 2016}}\n|-\n| ''[[D\u00e9racin\u00e9]]''\n| PlayStation 4 ([[PlayStation VR]])\n| {{dts|November 6, 2018}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | ''[[Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice]]''\n| Microsoft Windows\n| rowspan=3 | {{dts|March 22, 2019}}\n|-\n| PlayStation 4\n|-\n| Xbox One\n|-\n| rowspan=3 | ''[[Elden Ring]]''\n| Microsoft Windows\n| rowspan=3 | TBA\n|-\n| PlayStation 4\n|-\n| Xbox One\n|}\n\n== Game Philosophy ==\nFromSoftware is known for releasing highly difficult titles, notably the ''Souls series'', ''Bloodborne'', and ''Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice'', that lack difficulty settings.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vgr.com/fromsoftware-explains-why-its-games-dont-have-difficulty-levels/|title=FromSoftware Explains Why Its Games Don\u2019t Have Difficulty Levels|last=VGR|date=2018-06-19|website=VGR|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> [[Hidetaka Miyazaki]], the President of FromSoftware, justified the lack of difficulty settings, stating, \"We don't want to include a difficulty selection because we want to bring everyone to the same level of discussion and the same level of enjoyment. So we want everyone...to first face that challenge and to overcome it in some way that suits them as a player. We want everyone to feel that sense of accomplishment. We want everyone to feel elated and to join that discussion on the same level. We feel if there's different difficulties, that's going to segment and fragment the user base. People will have different experiences based on that [differing difficulty level]. This is something we take to heart when we design games. It's been the same way for previous titles and it's very much the same with ''Sekiro''.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.fromsoftware.jp/ww/}}\n\n{{FromSoftware games}}\n{{Kadokawa Dwango}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1986 establishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Software companies based in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Kadokawa Corporation subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:Japanese brands]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of Japan]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:Video game publishers]]\n", "name_user": "33hans33", "label": "safe", "comment": "Italicized a game.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FromSoftware"}
{"title_page": "C/1957 P1 (Mrkos)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Comet\n| name=C/1957 P1\n| image= Mrkos 1957A.jpg\n| caption= Comet Mrkos on August 27, 1957\n| discoverer=[[Anton\u00edn Mrkos]]\n| discovery_date=July, 1957\n| designations=Comet Mrkos, 1957 P1\n| epoch=2436040.5 (July 21, 1957)\n| semimajor=559 [[Astronomical Unit|AU]]\n| perihelion=0.355 AU<ref name=jpldata>{{cite web\n  |type=1958-07-09 last obs\n  |title=JPL Small-Body Database Browser: C/1957 P1 (Mrkos)\n  |url=https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=C/1957+P1\n  |publisher=[[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]]\n  |accessdate=2011-03-13}}</ref>\n| aphelion=1,117 AU\n| eccentricity=0.999365\n| period=\n| inclination= 93.9\u00b0\n| last_p=August 1, 1957\n| next_p= <!-- Calculated from future 1/a value from http://www.oaa.gr.jp/~oaacs/nk/nk837.htm because Solar System is n-body system. --> <!-- Solar System is not a two-body system. The previous or the next comet return cannot be calculated simply from current value of orbital period. Semi-major axis and orbital period will change during one revolution due to gravitational perturbations from planets. -->\n}}\n'''Comet Mrkos''', formally known as '''C/1957 P1''' (old style ''1957d''), was a non-periodical comet discoverd in 1957 by [[Anton\u00edn Mrkos]]. It was one of the two bright comets that had their perihelion in 1957, the other being [[Comet Arend\u2013Roland]]. Its peak magnitude was estimated to be around 1<ref>{{cite web |title=Brightest comets in the last two-thirds century |url=http://www.icq.eps.harvard.edu/brightest.html |website=www.icq.eps.harvard.edu |date=November 17, 2013}}</ref> and it has been characterised as a [[great comet]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Richter |first1=N. |title=II Cometary physics and the comets Arend-Roland and Mrkos |journal=Vistas in Astronomy |date=January 1960 |volume=3 |pages=132\u2013137 |doi=10.1016/0083-6656(60)90013-1}}</ref>\n\n== Observations ==\nThe comet was discovered by Czech astronomer Antonin Mrkos by [[naked eye]], at the observatory on [[Lomnick\u00fd \u0161t\u00edt]], [[Czechoslovakia]]. He announced its discovery on August 2, 1957 and by that point it was already discovered independently by others. However, the comet became known as comet Mrkos. The comet was then near perihelion and its [[apparent magnitude]] was estimated to be around 2.<ref name=\"Porter\">{{cite journal |last1=Porter |first1=J.G. |title=I Arend-Roland (1956h) and Mrkos (1957d) |journal=Vistas in Astronomy |date=January 1960 |volume=3 |pages=128\u2013132 |doi=10.1016/0083-6656(60)90012-X}}</ref>\n\nThe comet gradually moved away of the sun and became a conspicuous object visible after the sunset. The tail of the comet was estimated to be more than 5 degrees long. The comet had two tails, one that at the start was brighter and curved, and a straight one with knots that became brighter at the end of August and showed rapid changes in appearance. The comet remained visible by naked eye until the end of September.<ref name=\"Porter\"/>\n\nBy the end of October 1957, the comet had moved again close to the sun and wasn't observable. It was recovered at the end of January 1958 and it was last observed on July 9, 1958, when it was photographed as a 19 magnitude diffuse object.<ref name=\"Porter\"/>\n\nObservation of the comet revealed the presence of [[sodium]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Vainu Bappu |first1=M. K. |last2=Sinvhal |first2=S. D. |title=Polarization Measures of Comet Arend-Roland (1956h) and Comet Mrkos (1957d) |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society |date=1 February 1960 |volume=120 |issue=2 |pages=152\u2013162 |doi=10.1093/mnras/120.2.152}}</ref> and [[cyanide]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ferron |first1=Ignacio R. |title=On the CN (0, 0) spectrum of Comet Mrkos 1957d |journal=Astrophysics and Space Science |date=November 1977 |volume=52 |issue=1 |pages=11\u201316 |doi=10.1007/BF00647154}}</ref> in its spectrum, in the predicted values.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://ase.tufts.edu/cosmos/view_picture.asp?id=619 Telescopic view of the comet by Lick Observatory]\n\n{{Comets}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mrkos}}\n[[Category:Non-periodic comets]]\n[[Category:1956 in science]]\n[[Category:Astronomical objects discovered in 1957|19560802]]\n[[Category:Great comets]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Comet\n| name=C/1957 P1\n| image= Mrkos 1957A.jpg\n| caption= Comet Mrkos on August 27, 1957\n| discoverer=[[Anton\u00edn Mrkos]]\n| discovery_date=July, 1957\n| designations=Comet Mrkos, 1957 P1\n| epoch=2436040.5 (July 21, 1957)\n| semimajor=559 [[Astronomical Unit|AU]]\n| perihelion=0.355 AU<ref name=jpldata>{{cite web\n  |type=1958-07-09 last obs\n  |title=JPL Small-Body Database Browser: C/1957 P1 (Mrkos)\n  |url=https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=C/1957+P1\n  |publisher=[[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]]\n  |accessdate=2011-03-13}}</ref>\n| aphelion=1,117 AU\n| eccentricity=0.999365\n| period=\n| inclination= 93.9\u00b0\n| last_p=August 1, 1957\n| next_p= <!-- Calculated from future 1/a value from http://www.oaa.gr.jp/~oaacs/nk/nk837.htm because Solar System is n-body system. --> <!-- Solar System is not a two-body system. The previous or the next comet return cannot be calculated simply from current value of orbital period. Semi-major axis and orbital period will change during one revolution due to gravitational perturbations from planets. -->\n}}\n'''Comet Mrkos''', formally known as '''C/1957 P1''' (old style ''1957d''), was a non-periodical comet discoverd in 1957 by [[Anton\u00edn Mrkos]]. It was one of the two bright comets that had their perihelion in 1957, the other being [[Comet Arend\u2013Roland]]. Its peak magnitude was estimated to be around 1<ref>{{cite web |title=Brightest comets in the last two-thirds century |url=http://www.icq.eps.harvard.edu/brightest.html |website=www.icq.eps.harvard.edu |date=November 17, 2013}}</ref> and it has been characterised as a [[great comet]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Richter |first1=N. |title=II Cometary physics and the comets Arend-Roland and Mrkos |journal=Vistas in Astronomy |date=January 1960 |volume=3 |pages=132\u2013137 |doi=10.1016/0083-6656(60)90013-1}}</ref>\n\n== Observations ==\nThe comet was discovered by Czech astronomer Antonin Mrkos by [[naked eye]], at observatory on [[Lomnick\u00fd \u0161t\u00edt]], [[Czechoslovakia]]. He announced its discovery on August 2, 1957 and by that point it was already discovered independently by others. However, the comet became known as comet Mrkos. The comet was then near perihelion and its [[apparent magnitude]] was estimated to be around 2.<ref name=\"Porter\">{{cite journal |last1=Porter |first1=J.G. |title=I Arend-Roland (1956h) and Mrkos (1957d) |journal=Vistas in Astronomy |date=January 1960 |volume=3 |pages=128\u2013132 |doi=10.1016/0083-6656(60)90012-X}}</ref>\n\nThe comet gradually moved away of the sun and became a conspicuous object visible after the sunset. The tail of the comet was estimated to be more than 5 degrees long. The comet had two tails, one that at the start was brighter and curved, and a straight one with knots that became brighter at the end of August and showed rapid changes in appearance. The comet remained visible by naked eye until the end of September.<ref name=\"Porter\"/>\n\nBy the end of October 1957, the comet had moved again close to the sun and wasn't observable. It was recovered at the end of January 1958 and it was last observed on July 9, 1958, when it was photographed as a 19 magnitude diffuse object.<ref name=\"Porter\"/>\n\nObservation of the comet revealed the presence of [[sodium]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Vainu Bappu |first1=M. K. |last2=Sinvhal |first2=S. D. |title=Polarization Measures of Comet Arend-Roland (1956h) and Comet Mrkos (1957d) |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society |date=1 February 1960 |volume=120 |issue=2 |pages=152\u2013162 |doi=10.1093/mnras/120.2.152}}</ref> and [[cyanide]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ferron |first1=Ignacio R. |title=On the CN (0, 0) spectrum of Comet Mrkos 1957d |journal=Astrophysics and Space Science |date=November 1977 |volume=52 |issue=1 |pages=11\u201316 |doi=10.1007/BF00647154}}</ref> in its spectrum, in the predicted values.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://ase.tufts.edu/cosmos/view_picture.asp?id=619 Telescopic view of the comet by Lick Observatory]\n\n{{Comets}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mrkos}}\n[[Category:Non-periodic comets]]\n[[Category:1956 in science]]\n[[Category:Astronomical objects discovered in 1957|19560802]]\n[[Category:Great comets]]\n", "name_user": "C messier", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C/1957_P1_(Mrkos)"}
